@page
@model Portfolio.Web.Pages.Projects.StateExplorer.DetailsModel
@{
	Layout = "/Pages/Shared/_Layout.cshtml";
	ViewData["Title"] = "US State Explorer – Technical Details";
}

<link rel="stylesheet" href="~/css/gis.css" />

<div class="container py-5">

	<div class="mb-4 d-flex align-items-center justify-content-between gap-3">
		<h1 class="mb-0">🗺️ US State Explorer – Technical Details</h1>
		<a href="/Projects/StateExplorer" class="btn btn-outline-accent btn-sm flex-shrink-0" aria-label="Back to US State Explorer demo">
			<i class="fa-solid fa-arrow-left me-1"></i> Back to Demo
		</a>
	</div>

	<section class="theme-surface shadow-sm rounded p-4 mb-4">
		<h2 class="h4 mb-3">Architecture</h2>
		<p>
			The US State Explorer is built on a classic 4-layer ASP.NET Core architecture: a Razor Pages front end
			communicates with REST API controllers, which delegate to scoped services, which in turn query repositories
			backed by Entity Framework Core against SQL Server. The ArcGIS map rendering is handled entirely in the
			browser via the <strong>ArcGIS JavaScript SDK 4.x</strong>.
		</p>
		<p>
			Anonymous user identity is established via <code>AnonymousUserMiddleware</code>, which issues a secure
			HttpOnly cookie (<code>AnonUserId</code>) on first visit. This GUID is stored in
			<code>HttpContext.Items["AnonUserId"]</code> and used to scope all saved-feature operations to the
			visiting user without requiring authentication.
		</p>
		<p>
			Authenticated operations (Collections) require Google OAuth login through the
			<strong>Cookie + Google authentication schemes</strong>. The <code>Authenticated</code> policy gates
			those endpoints.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="theme-surface shadow-sm rounded p-4 mb-4">
		<h2 class="h4 mb-3">Technology Stack</h2>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>ArcGIS JavaScript SDK 4.x</strong> – MapView, FeatureLayer, Graphic, PopupTemplate, Typeahead search</li>
			<li><strong>ASP.NET Core (.NET 10)</strong> – Razor Pages host, API controllers, middleware pipeline</li>
			<li><strong>Entity Framework Core</strong> – SQL Server provider, fluent mappings, async queries</li>
			<li><strong>Bootstrap 5</strong> – responsive layout, dark-mode theming via CSS custom properties</li>
			<li><strong>Typeahead.js</strong> – client-side state name autocomplete</li>
			<li><strong>Google OAuth 2.0</strong> – authenticated user sign-in for Collections</li>
		</ul>
	</section>

	<section class="theme-surface shadow-sm rounded p-4 mb-4">
		<h2 class="h4 mb-3">Key Features</h2>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Interactive ArcGIS map</strong> – clickable state polygons with popup details fetched from the ArcGIS Sample Server 6 FeatureLayer</li>
			<li><strong>Saved Features</strong> – anonymous users can save any map feature; persisted per-user via <code>SavedFeatureService</code> and <code>SavedFeatureRepository</code></li>
			<li><strong>Collections</strong> – authenticated users can group saved features into named, colour-coded collections managed by <code>CollectionService</code></li>
			<li><strong>User Notes</strong> – inline notes attached to each saved feature, stored in the <code>UserNotes</code> EF entity</li>
			<li><strong>State search</strong> – Typeahead autocomplete wired to a client-side dataset; selecting a result zooms the map and highlights the state</li>
			<li><strong>Dark / light mode</strong> – toggled via a CSS class on <code>&lt;body&gt;</code>, persisted in <code>localStorage</code></li>
		</ul>
	</section>

	<section class="theme-surface shadow-sm rounded p-4 mb-4">
		<h2 class="h4 mb-3">Data Flow</h2>
		<ol>
			<li>Browser loads the ArcGIS MapView and queries <code>sampleserver6.arcgisonline.com</code> directly for FeatureLayer tiles and feature attributes.</li>
			<li>When a user saves a feature, the client POSTs to <code>POST /api/features</code>.</li>
			<li><code>SavedFeaturesController</code> reads the anonymous user GUID from <code>HttpContext.Items</code> (never from the request body) and delegates to <code>SavedFeatureService</code>.</li>
			<li><code>SavedFeatureService</code> enforces uniqueness and writes via <code>SavedFeatureRepository</code> inside an EF Core transaction.</li>
			<li>Saved features are returned with their <code>Collection</code> eagerly loaded so <code>MapToDto</code> can populate <code>CollectionName</code>.</li>
		</ol>
	</section>

	<section class="theme-surface shadow-sm rounded p-4 mb-4">
		<h2 class="h4 mb-3">Implementation Details</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>The front-end is split into focused ES modules: <code>mapManager.js</code> (map lifecycle), <code>featureService.js</code> (API calls), <code>collectionService.js</code> (collection CRUD), <code>stateStore.js</code> (client state), and <code>uiManager.js</code> (DOM updates).</li>
			<li>All API endpoints that touch per-user data filter by the anonymous GUID at the EF layer — never in the service.</li>
			<li>Multi-step writes (save feature + optional collection assignment) are wrapped in <code>BeginTransactionAsync / CommitAsync / RollbackAsync</code> to ensure atomicity.</li>
			<li>The <code>ArcGisService</code> proxies ArcGIS feature queries through the server, encoding caller-supplied values with <code>Uri.EscapeDataString</code> to prevent URL injection.</li>
		</ul>
	</section>

</div>
